You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel logic and dirty tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Navigation guard in `AppShell.xaml.cs` (catches swipe-back / hardware back)

The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the toolbar button, but users can also swipe back or press the Android hardware back button. Guard those with `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigating(args);

        // Only intercept back navigation (Pop)
        if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
            return;

        // Check if the current page is EditProductPage with unsaved changes
        if (CurrentPage?.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
            && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

            bool discard = await CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                args.Cancel();

            deferral.Complete();
        }
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation if the user taps "Stay".
- The guard checks `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so it only fires on back navigation, not forward pushes.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` bypasses `OnNavigating` (it runs your command instead), so both paths show the confirmation dialog independently.
